History of IBM: From cheese slices to flights in the cosmos.
IBM (International Business Machines) was born in New York a hundred years ago; it initially had the complicated name of Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It took the name IBM in 1924 - initially it was a brand used by a branch of a firm in Canada and South America.
The basis of the future IBM was the merger of four firms whose history is linked to the 1980s of the nineteenth century.
They had technologies such as the old "pointers", the pendulums that recorded the arrival and departure of employees.
The architect of the new company was Charles Ranlett Flint who until 1930 presided over the company's Supervisory Board.
Flint hired the head of a competing firm Thomas J. Watson to help him lead the company.
The leader then shadowed the founder of the firm - it is on Watson's ideas that until now the identity and culture of society are based.
Watson ran the kuss firm until 1952.
IBM, as its name says, began with the production of all possible machines for business and trade - cheese and meat slicers up to the cash registers.
In the first four years of Watson's leadership, revenue grew to $9 million and the company's expansion began in all parts of the world.
Watson was for the firm so irreplaceable that after 40 years of management it was his son who occupied the chair of director, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his direction IBM began the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s IBM's people and computers helped NASA guide flights in the cosmos - on Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the flight on the Moon.
Meanwhile in 1964 IBM developed the first computer family - the IBM System/360.
The classic PC that determines the computer standard of the time with the name of IBM 5150 arrived on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later IBM sold its computer factory to the Chinese company Lenovo, but bought the company of Consulting Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to take care of advice and services with high added value.
The strategy that has succeeded IBM over the past three years - is the Smarter Planet concept "a smarter planet".
Its objective is the intelligent use of technology in areas that have not yet been exploited, such as transport and city management.
As far as IBM is concerned, a "Smarter Commerce" platform recently developed that helps traders manage the entire business cycle.
IBM also has a strong history on our territory.
She created her branch in Czechoslovakia in 1932, then the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM RT, there is also Brno's strategic outsourcing centre.
The Central for Central and Eastern Europe is based in Prague and there is also the global research and development team responsible for the recognition of the word.
