How travel prices have changed since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered trips mainly to the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists traveled for holidays in East Germany, Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A major exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when he was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia and then the regime began to have an inclination for the west and travel to Yugoslavia was very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for the citizens of the socialist bloc (also for the Czechoslovaks) to travel individually even within the framework of the socialist countries.
If the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter otherwise the individual trip was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West, however, it was necessary to queue all night with a sleeping bag or to have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that it wasn't won yet.
The foreign exchange agreement that was the condition to travel to the west was denied to "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
However, the Czechoslovak currency was not exchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial resources without the currency agreement (Western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs most often spent their holidays in the country where there were therefore many cottages and cottages that the Czechs bought and this habit lasts until now.
Since 1989 the voyages of the Czechs have undergone a great revolution.
Although until 1989 holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were maximum, the Czechs spent last year abroad 4 million holiday days in countries around the world.
The great paradox that we are not aware of today is that the most popular country is Croatia, where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because part of Yugoslavia of the time.
The abolition of visas in the 1990s of the last century in the neighbouring countries of the west caused a huge wave of short-term visits, especially in Austria in Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not for a long time travel by plane to the west that everyone wanted to see at least a moment.
For example, in Paris travel organizations made Czechs sleep in tents in parks because our income did not allow us to pay the hotel or a pension.
The typical feature of a trip from Czech was at that time to take away his own canned food, sausage, etc... to save.
Another important moment was the interchangeability of the Czech krona, which allowed our tourists finally after decades of being able to freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living and the average wage have increased what has caused around 1997 another important moment.
With increasing demand for travel, travel agencies have started to prepare tours with air charter connections since 1997 which, thanks to contracts, have dramatically reduced costs compared to what was before.
At the end of the 90s of the last century, Czechs had visa-free links with virtually most developed countries around the world apart from the US that later facilitated our journeys.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when the first air charter was prepared for an exotic country, Thailand, from the Czech Republic.
Since this year as every year direct air charters take Czech tourists to distant hot countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolutionary development arrived in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the EU abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to fully join the group of developed countries.
In 2008 also the Czechs for the first time in history spent more than half of their vacation abroad (50.3%) and for the first time again in history spent more than 15,000 kroner per person on vacation abroad including the associated expenses.
