Facebook boasts so much personal information, says Jamie Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the site's advertising tool to find the people they have been looking for with scientific precision - the way marketers have been doing it for years.
Jamie Bartlett's team discovered that half a million members are fans of far right groups in Europe. She targeted them with ads, but instead of linking them to a new group or product, the ads invited users to answer a survey. The questions asked concerned their level of education, their attitudes to violence and their optimism about their own future.
By contacting these people through Facebook, Jamie Bartlett and his colleagues were able to question 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - without leaving the office.
"This is a new way of doing research," says Jamie Bartlett.
Some results are not surprising at all: online supporters of right-wing groups are rather men, young people and against immigration.
But surprisingly, "those who associate online and offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who remain behind their computer screen."
DEMOS's study is just one example of how Facebook has become the new tool in the hands of scientists.
Reflection groups, medical researchers and polytologists use the site to study all topics that affect health issues such as social trends, thanks to "Like", publications on walls and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding on average three contents per day, the "supernova data" generates an explosion in research, increasing the number of research works whose site name appears in the title by almost 800% compared to the last five years.
For some researchers, the advantage of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you couldn't approach on the street.
"Before, when you tried to investigate the people of the British national party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You were supposed to go to the party, but they would never have allowed you to enter," says Jamie Bartlett.
"Facebook avoids all this - you have direct access to their information."
Others say that the site could provide a way to identify and address health and social problems.
According to a recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison, and his colleagues, young students who spoke on Facebook about their drunken exploits were much more likely to be alcoholic than discreet students in this regard.
Megan Moreno suggests that students' colleagues, such as counselors, could monitor the site and intervene to possibly help a student whose status would speak too often of alcohol.
"You can't deal with a problem if you don't diagnose it," said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Megan Moreno and director of the Centre for Children's Health, Behaviour and Development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle, the Washington Post.
"We know how to identify children at risk, and who would not otherwise be recognized."
Facebook also constantly accesses the information of its users.
The team of the data site studied statistics on Valentine's Day and Valentine's Day, the 2010 mid-term election participation rate, and a national happiness index (through information only available - the digital freedom champions have long argued that the site could make its data treasure available to other people for research purposes).
But Facebook users know that the site looks at them, whether they like them or not - in exchange for being able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of kilometers away, the site is allowed to access your information.
But what happens when Facebook users are part of an investigation they haven't even heard of?
While researchers have well-defined instructions on how to collect information other than through the Internet, there is anything else online.
"I don't think a lot of users have ever thought about the fact that a researcher can study their profile," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, according to a 2006 study he conducted by observing the Facebook walls of his students.
"As far as they know, the exchanges were only seen by their friends."
Then comes the question of methodology.
Even without going through the Internet, there is no guarantee that the subject of a study is completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know the degree of truth of a profile or on a user's wall.
