In the first year of management of Mario López Valdez, in Sinaloa unemployment and informality have increased, foreign investment has decreased and the economy has contracted
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of the government of Mario López Valdez, self-called of change, which has generated great expectations regarding the advances of the economy, but given the climate adversity of the beginning of the year, the increase is not observed, in exchange there is a deterioration of the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures of February, apart from causing losses of billions for the agricultural sector, have limited the possibilities of the state economy for growth, caused a contraction of economic activity in general by 3.6 per cent in the first half of the year, mainly justified by the historical decline of 31.16 per cent in agriculture, which has affected the dynamism of the other economic sectors.
According to the report of assignments by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, there was damage of 582 million 835 hectares cultivated, of which 78.03 per cent suffered total damage and the remainder of 21.07 per cent suffered partial damage, the main crops affected were vegetables, corn and chickpeas.
The decline in economic activity has led to a steady increase in unemployment in the State until November, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the rate of unemployment of the State during the first three quarters of the year has been observed, as while from January to March 55 thousand and 053 Signanoens were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 per cent of the Active Economic Population, in the second quarter the rate has become 5.28 per cent and from July to September the average has continued to rise to 6.19 per cent, a rate that represents more than 74 thousand Signanoens unemployed, an increase compared to the first half of 18 thousand 969 people.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multi-factory, according to economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the UAS Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly according to the actions carried out by public policy.
"What we see is an increase in unemployment that is due to various factors, among which the loss of liquidity in the market due to a restriction of resources by the legislation approved in Congress to combat money laundering, because for people who earn dollars illegally it is not easy for them to work to win them, to invest them and to use them in something," he says.
Migration in custody
López Cervantes reported that the rise in unemployment is also due to a demographic factor.
"The number of people leaving the state to go to work abroad, in the United States has been limited, first because of the difficulties of entry and second because when they enter they already have a lot of difficulty in finding work, these people stay here and ask for sources of work, which causes unemployment to rise," he said.
Lack of seriousness
The analysis of the labour market in signaroen is worsening considering the high level of lack of seriousness that predominates between the working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 per cent of the population employed in this state works there without contributing as a worker to any social insurance institution.
Apart from unemployment and lack of seriousness, another reason for the state's shift is the low wages, the entity has the lowest wages in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Institute of Social Insurance and the Secretariat of Labour and Social Forecasting.
The average monthly earnings of the workers of Signano were, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, much lower than the national average, which is 7 thousand 375 pesos.
FDI contraction
Apart from the decline in economic activity and the rise in unemployment, in 2011 there was the largest reduction in Direct Foreign Investment over the past 10 years, according to the Economy Secretariat from January to June, State FDI reached $630 thousand,697, representing a decrease of 87.74 per cent compared to the $5,143,000,312 recorded in the same period of the previous year.
In turn, the Secretariat for Economic Development of the Government of the State accounts for a total investment of 17,280 billion pesos per year, mainly recorded by companies in the tertiary sector.
Debt
In view of the economic contraction scenario, the Government of the State requested in July the approval of a 3 billion pesos loan for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the aim of reactivating the economy, the approval of the State Congress was 2,600 billion pesos and until November no debt benefits were observed in any sector of the State economy.
Reactions
For representatives of the employer sector, Mario López Valdés' first year of government demonstrates a lack of government management capacity.
Miguel Loredo López, President of the National Chamber of Transformation Industry, said that in 2011 there was no harmonization of the wishes of the various sectors, including the Government of the State.
"The performance of Sinaloa's economy during this year was really very poor, we have to work hard to recover the land we lost this year, in 2012 we have to double our efforts, we had to align the effort of all and above all the good work already synchronized of this new government team, hope that next year will be much better," he said.
Economic slowness
Loredo López stated that events such as the frosts of the beginning of the year have retained the economy of the state and restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including frosts, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows us to have an acceptable level of flow in trials, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we close well below the expectations we had," he says.
Redefining the vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of the Mexican Republic of Sinaloa, said that we want to channel the state to productive activities of more dynamism.
"In general terms we have observed that we have worked, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term programme that redefines the vocation and economic direction of the State, because it is important that we detonate the full potential of Sinaloa's material and human resources," he says.
A lot to do
