The Court valids "analogue cut" in Mexico in 2015
Substitution of analog signals by digitals is one of the most important changes the world has suffered in recent years
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) has rejected the constitutional controversy that the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have formulated against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analogue cut" from 2021 to 2015, because the eight necessary votes to invalidate it have not been gathered.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his responsibilities when he issued the decree detailing the actions to be taken to implement the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic was rejected for not reaching the qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality of the decree, and this continues to be in force.
The draft award, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed the decree's declaration as non-constitutional, because the regulations on radio and television are a statutory assignment to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), contrary to the principles of hierarchical subordination and reservation of law.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero were voted in favour of the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have promoted two constitutional disputes to challenge the decree and by admitting the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero has suspended the application of the decree and all its actions for the digital transition.
The plenary session of ministers also decided to dismiss the complaint made by the Chamber of Deputies, without discussing the project that Minister Sánchez Cordero is also responsible for.
In his intervention, the Minister President said that he disagreed with the project's arguments, in that the Federal Executive cannot structure through general standards the measures for public administration to prepare for it.
"I do not consider that it would affect the autonomy of the regulator," he recalled that planning public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the Federal Executive, which has the constitutional mandate to lead the state.
The substitution of analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years and this results in better exploitation of radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
To postpone the change, he argued, would be to postpone the benefits of digitisation which implies a decision of public interest that not only has a technical dimension, "because it also includes economic, social, political and national security issues".
These issues, he stressed, "requiring the operation of a whole system establishes, in accordance with the principle of economic direction of the State, includes a group of attributions that the Constitution grants to the faculty of the Executive of the State".
He recalled that a large number of countries from all over the world have already completed the digital transition and have done so through the Executive, despite the fact that they have highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, by issuing the contested decree, has in a form invaded the sphere of competence of the Congress, because it ensures in the administrative sphere the respect of the laws issued by the Legislature, he said.
