The appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet Wednesday with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and put the whole Eurozone at risk.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed Sunday, would meet Wednesday with the president, Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm that he can form the Government.
It is expected that he will present a cabinet composed in its majority by technocrats, even if it is not clear when the new executive will assume his position.
Monti said he was going to present to the president the result of his conversations with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," said the former European Commissioner to journalists.
Monti did not say explicitly that he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles were overcome.
"The frame is now well drawn," he added.
Monti has completed the process to form a government in less than three days, in a shorter time than normally, while Italy is fighting a political and financial crisis that has pushed the costs of its debt to levels impossible to sustain.
The new administration led by the former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package required by European leaders to regain confidence in Italy that had been affected.
Highlighting the pressure on Monti to hurry, the instability of the markets placed the performance of the Italian bonds BTP at 10 years over 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to be saved.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of the Italian employer Confindustria, told the media after her meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government a lot."
We believe that this Government is the last opportunity for Italy to emerge from this emergency situation.
Monti's chances of success have been greatly stimulated by the support of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, which forced the crisis to resign last Saturday.
"We believe that the efforts of Professor Monti will have a good result," said Angelino Alfano, secretary of the center-right party.
The support of PDL, the largest Italian party, is significant because so far many of its members have opposed the technocrat majority government that Monti forms.
Parliamentary support
Monti's new government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what is likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockage or delay in its efforts could cause a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks added to the pressure by observing that a bankruptcy of Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began his consultations with political parties, trade unions and employers' groups and youth and women's organizations on Monday.
He'll finish his meeting tour Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who authorized an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it was clear that Berlusconi would resign, the costs of the Italian debt have now returned to critical levels between uncertainty about the success of the new Prime Minister.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of 1.9 trillion euros, would be too much for the current financial defences of Eurozone.
Monti said that his Government should persist until the forthcoming elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians would only give him time to implement reforms before advancing the elections.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist that he should be trained only by specialists, an indication of their objections to a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources have indicated that mutual mistrust and disagreements between parties complicate the attempt to include political figures.
