MSS announces protocol to find the gene of obesity
Social Insurance directs an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in the case of children and young people; this is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in the case of children and young people, called the 'Genetic Protocol of Obesity of Children and Adolescents', which will allow the markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the Head of the Medical Investigation Unit in Biochemistry of the Specialty Hospital of the National Medical Centre of the 20th Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and graduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Advanced Research and Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The investigation invites the right-wing or non-right-wing population to attend the IMSS participating sports units in Valle de México, where the evidence is made to minors every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Sports Unit Cuauhtémoc (Estado de México Poniente) and that from 8 October, the activity takes place in the Sports Unit of Nezahualcoyolt (Estado de México Oriente).
After reaching the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Sports Independence Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Sports Morelos Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the objective of this investigation and that of knowing the components and the importance of genetics with regard to the development of obesity and identifying risk factors for children and young Mexicans in order to prevent the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
As the World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on November 14, he mentioned that the goal is to bring together three thousand children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and under the supervision of their parents, for the application of the specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and family heritage history of their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that on Saturdays anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetic levels will be applied to all participants (an attempt is made to identify people associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López reported that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys reported that in only six years there has been an increase, for boys, of 77 per cent in obesity and for girls of 47 per cent; for overweight there has also been a dramatic increase,' stressed the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country is different from others by its genetic history.
He reported that, on average, Mexicans have 65 per cent Indo-American heredity, 30 per cent European and 5 per cent African, and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy consumed (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the full assessment of the children, which allows to detect whether they have a degree of overweight or obesity.
He even said that the presence of dark-colored folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm indicate the probability of suffering from metabolic and even pre-diabetes alterations.
The information is managed in a confidential manner, the doctors hand it over in writing to the parents, who are informed of each of the measures and changes in their lifestyle to prevent disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentaryism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, stay most of the day sitting in front of the TV and use means of transport instead of walking on short distances.
Another cause is the high calorie intake, i.e. the highest consumption of sweet drinks, carbohydrates (tamales - corn meal meat paste wrapped in corn leaves - bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would avoid cassis
Rafael Herrera, researcher at UNAM's Faculty of Chemistry, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better yield, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the reports were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair approximately 200 thousand cassis each rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of Valle de México, warns Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of the bituminous peacock is adequate, the cassis could be reduced or even eliminated completely.
During his conference A technological opinion on cassis, organized as part of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory to which he is responsible develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture having characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera considered that this type of modified asphalts could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, like some cities in the north of the country, to improve the yield, and therefore the formation of the cassiums.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbons molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the paving its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behaviour of asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, at almost 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very large and at 50 degrees C it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, asphalt becomes broken, he added.
This means that in the streets the asphalt resistance is not uniform and changes during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, warns the chemical engineering specialist.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City were mostly covered by a flexible pavement, composed of six layers of materials, the last three of which involved asphalt.
Among the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and subsequently compacted.
Each of the small stones that forms the layer, he pointed out, is bathed an asphalt.
When vehicles pass through it by generating effort, it allows forces to spread very well in the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, they would spread better, thought the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt layer, he says, one last layer called rolling layer, made of fine stone, that is, sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
Since this is the layer in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and provide adhesion in the street.
As the part of the paving that receives and distributes the efforts, the rolling layer also requires that it be of adequate thickness and the material it is made of must be treated.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, is also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he says, as they significantly affect asphalt layer performance.
When the soil is wet, the water pours inside the layer is difficult for it to come out, which softens all layers of the pavement and therefore causes the cassis.
In the process of forming a cassis, he said, the first one to be ruined is the rolling film and only later is affected the asphalt layer, but the damage does not take place immediately, but it is a process that must be treated at the first signs with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Researchers explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor for the formation of cassies and therefore the thickness of each layer of the paving must always be linked to the load of vehicles and guarantee its satisfaction, in order to avoid frequent formation of cassies.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow to repair the cassions easily and without having to use high temperatures.
