So was the work of Cali's person who identified the corpse of Alfonso Cano
A Cali typewriter went into history like the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is crucial.
Last November 4, a typewriter from the Cali ITC passed into history as the person who confirmed the identity of the supreme leader of the Farcs: "Alfonso Cano", comparing his fingerprints.
Of the seven typists working in the local offices of the ITC, this week was the "availability" of Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working for 21 years in the field of judicial investigation.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in the municipalities of Chocó, where many times he had to spend more than five days in the forest to get to the place where the dead bodies were to be identified.
In 2000 he moved to the capital of Valle and after taking appropriate courses, he specialized in typing, which is the study of friction skin, i.e. the palms and feet.
During the week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano, Eliazar had been warned to take clothes with him for at least three days.
Something very big was waiting for him.
Friday night he left for Cauca in a Palmira helicopter.
He knew that he had to identify two bodies and that one of them was suspected of being the man who was leading the oldest guerrilla in the world, so he was asked to take the card with the ten fingerprints of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
But when he arrived with the investigation team at the place of the body, he did not recognize it by its physical appearance, because it was very different from the one he had seen in the media.
He didn't have a beard, he was dressed as a peasant in the area, without glasses and much thinner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Accompanied by a galtonian wolf, ink, a picker and a lantern, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the body with those of the map.
His eye did not deceive him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was the one who confirmed to the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón that yes, he was the supreme leader of the Farcs.
Looking for the fingerprint
For a typologist from Sijín de Cali the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos made to Eliazar González, in a press conference for the operation against "Cano", is very significant.
A lot of people don't know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an accurate science, without margin of error, which can be crucial in solving crimes.
In addition to identifying the bodies, typists support investigations into crimes such as theft and homicide and confirm the identity of the captured persons.
When captured, many offenders present false identity cards or do not have documents.
We take their fingerprints and look for them in the database.
The researcher reported that in a case of theft he had to remove part of the wall from a house, because in that place the thief had supported his hand to get out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not adequate surfaces to draw a fingerprint, but in this case we were able to get the print from all hands and identify the offender who had participated in different flights," he recalls.
Fingerprints may also rule out or confirm suspects in homicide cases.
Recently we found a dead man, with bottles of drink around him.
By means of the investigation, it was determined that a parent could be suspected of the crime and indeed a print on the bottle coincided.
Even if it doesn't guarantee that he's the killer, it puts him on the scene of the crime.
A CTI typewriter explained that "the fingerprints of objects with chemical or physical reagents" are extracted.
When they appear, a picker or tape is used to pick them up.
Subsequently, the prints are sent to Asif, the database of the declines, or to the National Civil Registry.
"The problem is that there are still a lot of undocumented Colombians," said the ITC expert.
He explained that everything is not how it is shown in the CSI television program.
Like everything that shines isn't gold, everything you touch doesn't necessarily become a print.
However, it can be used if the necessary confrontation is achieved.
The "indigns" challenge the authorities in New York
Hundreds of protesters roamed in front of Zuccotti Square to camp there.
A large part of the population accessed the evacuation order and moved to a nearby park.
The members of the Occupy Wall Street movement challenged the New York authorities this Tuesday by trying to re-enter, through a court order, instead of Manhattan, from where they were evacuated at dawn and when they tried to occupy another park in the Great Apple.
Hundreds of protesters roamed in front of Zuccotti Square, where they wanted to access through a court order that allows 'indignant' to camp again in this place, while the other side of the movement responded to the evacuation by occupying a park further north of the city, where there were new arrests.
"Our idea is that if the court does not allow us to camp again in the square, we will settle in another place and continue the legal struggle to return to Zuccotti, and through sit-ins and peaceful demonstrations," said one of the spokespersons of the Occupy Wall Street movement, Mark Bray.
Bray explained that the response of the 'indigns' to the evacuation of their camp personally dictated by the mayor of New York, Michael Bloomberg, came to the courts, where Justice Lucy Billings issued an order prohibiting the forced evacuation of the place and allowing protesters to stay in the camp.
In addition, the 'indigns' occupied a new park located at the confluence of Canal Street and Sixth Avenue, very close to the entrance to the Holland Tunnel, which unites New York and New Jersey, owned by Trinity Church parish.
At least for an hour they managed to occupy the place, but after the police moved there and arrested some protesters, even though Bray could not confirm the concrete figure, ensuring Efe that he saw some journalists who had also been handcuffed.
The organization ensures that there are hundreds of people who had settled in this place, where a delegation of religious leaders moved in as a sign of support to the members of the movement and tried to intervene in favor of them before the police.
Meanwhile, the Zuccotti Square - which is a private-owned chamber - remains closed pending the holding of a court hearing scheduled for this Tuesday, during which the legality of this morning's evacuation must be analysed.
Some protesters who had been displaced to that point were carrying and distributing copies of this court order at that time and even handing it over to the agents who were watching the square, which caused 'some small clashes', Bray said, who denounced the fact that some officials struck the protesters.
The court order prohibits the authorities from evacuating the members of Occupy Wall Street or from applying 'laws published after the beginning of the occupation or from prohibiting protesters from re-entering the park with tents or other properties they used before'.
Mayor Bloomberg told the press that, as a result of this judicial order, the city had suspended the reopening of space to the public and protesters, but warned that local laws did not allow them to settle with tents and sleeping bags.
The municipal councillor personally defended the evacuation carried out at dawn in Zuccotti Square, an operation during which 200 people were arrested and decided because the demonstrators 'violate the law'.
Bloomberg explained that he had given the order to evacuate the place because it became "a place where people did not come to protest, but to violate laws and in some cases, to hurt others", because "some shops had received threats" and residents were afraid "for their quality of life".
"The evacuation of this morning at dawn has been repugnant and shows that Bloomberg is more interested in defending the financial interests than those of American workers," added the spokesman for the movement, who accuses the mayor of "not respecting freedom of expression".
Officials of Occupy Wall Street also indicated that they do not plan to organize "great actions" for Thursday in collaboration with community organizations and trade unions to commemorate the two months of protests, which began on September 17.
