Japan Reigns After Earthquake
GDP rose by 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and ended the fall spiral in early March
Since March the Japanese economy has been paralysed, convalescent even after the devastating earthquake that has become a nuclear crisis, the worst disaster in the country since the Second World War.
The first estimates by the Government of Tokyo have calculated material losses at $300,000 million, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, seems to have diminished.
After three consecutive quarters of falls, the Gross Domestic Product data between July and September were used to turn the page permanently: GDP increased by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and 6% in annualized rates.
The second quarter - for Japanese, the fiscal year starts in March 2012 - also assumes the highest rate of increase from January to March 2010.
Recovery is partly due to the resumption of equipment acquisitions to restore the areas devastated by the earthquake and the post-tsunami earthquake.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the 0.9% decrease in capital expenditures observed from January to March, the first decline after six months of unbroken growth.
However, the real stimulus of the Japanese economy is not based solely on the Keynesian impulse that calls for taking advantage of the crisis to consolidate - or rebuild - the infrastructure, to use the deficiencies to grow from zero.
Japan woke up mainly thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japan's GDP.
This variable increased by 1%, driven by increased spending on vehicles, travel and entertainment activities.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo returned to the internal market when the yen - the Japanese currency - became one of the "security value havens" elected by investors fleeing the Eurozone debt crisis and the United States forecast disturbances, a privilege that weighs like a slab in the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger divide, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic floating line is determined by the health of major technological groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, took responsibility for their poor results between July and September for the yen's contribution.
While markets continue to remain in peripheral EU countries, Yoshihiko Noda's government does not decrease custody.
"We must monitor the risks that persist, such as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of the floods in Thailand and the rapid appreciation of the yen," said Secretary of State for Economic Policy, Motohisa Furukawa yesterday.
And indeed, the prospects are not at all encouraging.
The Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) mentioned that the majority of member countries presented clearer signs of economic slowdown in September.
The indicator that anticipates the inflection points of the world economy has highlighted that the main powers are constrained.
Because it dropped four decimals to 100.4 points, compared to 100.8 in August.
Eurozone has even been below the average, which is in level 100, with eight decimal places down to 99.13 points.
Athens again feeds doubts
Papadimos says the adjustments will be approved, but the Conservatives will not sign any written commitments
With the peripheral risk premiums triggered and the uncertainty re-installed in the parks, Greece continues to interfere in the maze that leads to the exit from the great crisis of European debt.
The feeling that the "consensus" of the new Hellenic Transitional Government is rather imposed by the requirements of Brussels than by a real conviction of political forces is beginning to be confirmed by the facts.
While the new Prime Minister, Lukas Papadimos pointed out yesterday that there is no alternative for structural reforms and that the 100-day period established in his appointment may be short to apply them, the leader of the Conservative New Democracy party, Antonis Samaras, assured that he would not support the new austerity measures in any case and reiterated his requirement for new elections for the scheduled date, that of 19 February.
"The main task of this Government is to implement the decisions of the 26 October summit," Papadimos said when he opened a parliamentary debate yesterday that will end tomorrow with a vote of confidence for the new Executive.
A package of 24 programmes to stimulate employment, reform of the disciplinary code for civil servants and new measures against tax evasion will be the first initiatives.
However, Samaras' message does not raise doubts about his position: "We are committed to helping the Transitional Government, but we are not committed to anything else".
The conservative leader has gone a step further in his pulse than the EU and IMF, the bodies that need to unlock the 8,000 million that Athens urgently needs, and has made it clear that he will not approve any letter of commitment to carry out the adjustments.
But the European Commission, still irritated by the impact caused by the vantage of the Papandreu referendum, reiterated yesterday that its requirement is firm: it will not unlock the aid if the new Government and the leaders of the main Hellenic parties do not sign "a written commitment without ambiguity as soon as possible".
The spokesman for Economic Affairs, Amadeu Altafaj, explained that the Troika inspectors would return "very quickly" to Athens to discuss with the new Government "the elements necessary to pay the sixth tranche" of 8,000 million, even if there is no final date either.
The Greeks still have a lot to do.
Queen Sofia: "These are instruments for progress and hope"
The Queen stresses Spain's "preponderant" place with regard to this type of finance
Spain "has reached a prominent place at the global level in the role of Microfinance".
Queen Sofia recalled that in the past two decades the country has become the world's second largest donor in terms of this instrument of cooperation, the essence of which lies in the fact that it is an "instrument for social progress, justice and hope in a better future for all humanity, based on trust in the human being".
Yesterday, the Queen inaugurated the Fifth World Microcredit Summit in Valladolid with the certainty that "there is no doubt" that this type of operation is "absolutely indispensable" to achieve the 2015 United Nations Millennium Goals and, "very specifically, in the one that aims to halve the volume of people living with income under one dollar per day, to which the "poverty threshold" is set.
Spain "continues to work" to expand the network of beneficiaries "in every corner of the world, and undertakes this task with "responsibility", said Queen Sofia, who hoped that initiatives and inputs originating during the Summit, which will extend until Thursday, "ensure the creation of new capacities and better opportunities for the poorest and especially for women", the main beneficiaries of these loans.
We have "achieved many goals" and "we face many challenges".
The Microcredit Summit is envisaged not only as a forum for debate, but also as the platform from which to push "two basic goals".
Thus, Her Majesty explained that the goal is that at the end of 2015 there are 175 million poor families who have accessed these financial services and that one hundred million of these families are coming out of the poverty line in which they now live.
The impulse in the design of microcredits in Spain and the rest of the world "has followed the path initiated a few years ago in a pioneering way" by Muhammad Yunus, emphasized Queen Sofia as a "act of justice and recognition due".
And she described the father of this instrument as an "admirable idealist in the universal cause of the fight against poverty", the work she has known for 15 years, when the Queen travelled to Bangladesh to know her lending policy on the ground.
This experience was followed a year later by the first World Summit in Washington and other meetings such as those held in Côte d'Ivoire in 1999, Canada in 2006, and "at each meeting I was able to see a continuous evolution," said Her Majesty, whose relationship with this project brought yesterday the qualifier of "head of the family" gathered in Valladolid by the "banking of the poor".
Finally, Queen Sofia finished her speech by encouraging those present to participate in the debate and in the search for solutions to move forward in the fight against poverty.
"Ethical imperative"
Foreign Minister Trinidad Jiménez warned that solidarity "is an ethical imperative" for any democratic state.
In that regard, she explained that it would be a mistake to link cooperation with developing countries to times of economic prosperity, as it is a "permanent obligation".
Jiménez considered that microcredits imply "a serious and rigorous policy dedicated to the eradication of poverty", and now "more than ever" the governments of developed countries must work on solidarity criteria and not let it be the victim of compressions.
For Spain, microcredit is "one of the main lines of development cooperation".
The Secretary of State for International Cooperation, Soraya Rodriguez, applauded "the success" of giving "confidence" to the "excluded" people to whom all closed the door"; and the mayor of Valladolid, Francisco Javier León de la Riva, welcomed the people present in a city that "opens its contaminated doors of the spirit of solidarity".
The CDU proposes to elect the European President by universal suffrage
The first day of the Congress of the Christian-Democratic Union (CDU), Monday, November 14, in Leipzig, took place without real difficulty for Angela Merkel, Chancellor but also President of the Christian-Democratic Party.
