What is fraud at the time of illness?
After the allowances, the UMP and the government launch the disease stop offensive.
Nicolas Sarkozy will be on Tuesday 15 November in Bordeaux to visit a family allowance fund, and to deliver a speech on the theme - recurring since 2007 - of the fight against social fraud and assistance.
And to accompany this offensive, which starts from a desire to make savings in a context of rigour, but is no less indicative of an axis of the presidential campaign to the right, the majority wants to focus on the sick stops.
Firstly, for the purpose of budget savings: the government plans to impose a fourth day's deficit on employees of the private sector before taking over a work stoppage.
Clearly, without a specific company agreement, an employee who falls ill would lose four days' pay, so at least 15% of his monthly income.
A measure that could provoke anger, but which would bring back 280 million euros, according to Les Echos.
And that would be accompanied by another measure, of more symbolic scope: to impose on civil servants a day of non-compensation in the event of a stoppage of work (they do not have until now a period of deprivation, as opposed to three days in the private).
While these issues are under discussion, the majority also re-launches the issue of fraud, focusing this time on the abuses linked to work stoppages.
"Controls will be much more important and, in addition, if you are taken, you will refund," warned Xavier Bertrand at the RTL microphone on Sunday, November 13.
As in other cases, the advertising effects seem somewhat disproportionate to the reality of fraud at work.
It has been the subject of constant monitoring and political offensives since 2002, most of which have borne fruit.
The French are no more ill than elsewhere in Europe.
Let us focus first on national figures.
According to the National Health Insurance Fund (CNAM), more than EUR 237 million of daily allowances were issued in 2006.
According to the Institute for Health Economics Research and Documentation, daily allowances accounted for 5% of health expenditure in 2008, with EUR 11.3 billion.
Of this amount, 46% concerned maternity leave and accidents at work, and 54% concerned sick leave, or EUR 6.2 billion.
And so 2.5% of health spending.
In 2010, the French experienced an average of 14.5 working days, compared to 17.8 in 2009, according to a study by the Alma Consulting group.
An average that hides some differences: another survey, published in 2007 by the career management site Monster.com, showed that 75% of the 40,000 French employees interviewed said they had not taken any sick days.
Another study, this time of Sickness Insurance , states that in 2010, 37% of sick leave was less than 8 days, 22% from 8 to 14 days, 15% from 15 days to one month, 15% from one to three months and 11% beyond.
When compared with their European neighbours, French employees are no more inclined than elsewhere to stop work.
A long study conducted in 2010 by two CNRS researchers showed that between 1994 and 2001, the overall absence rate (for health reasons or not) in France ranged between 10% and 11%, compared to 20% and 28% in Denmark, 15% in the United Kingdom or 16% and 18% in the Netherlands.
Sickness fraud represents very little in the face of work in the dark.
As for fraud, it only reaches a small extent.
The strengthening of legislation since 2002 makes systematic checks on sick leave more than 45 days.
In 2008, out of 1.5 million controls, CNAM found that 13% of the 285 000 completed for short-term stops were "unwarranted or too long", or 37,050 cases.
In the case of stops of more than 45 days, systematically controlled, there were 11% "unadapted or unjustified" cases out of 1.2 million, or 132 000.
In total, therefore, 169,000 "unjustified" cases, out of several million employees who had had a sick leave.
A figure that represents very little, for example, compared to work in the dark.
According to MP UMP Dominique Tian, the author of a report on the issue in June, the latter would represent 9-15 billion euros of tax loss per year, more than the total cost of daily allowances, and therefore infinitely more than the fraud of the latter.
Papademos: Greece will have to implement a new adjustment plan
Greece will need a new adjustment programme to restore its economy.
This is what the Prime Minister, Lucas Papadémos, said Monday, November 14, in front of Parliament, adding that the 100 days given to his union government would not be enough to accomplish this task.
"In order to continue the economic recovery efforts, we need the support of our European partners and a new fiscal adjustment programme," said the head of government, who delivered his first public speech at the opening of the debate on the vote of confidence in Parliament on Wednesday.
The implementation of the decisions taken at the euro area summit on 27 October will be the "principal task" of the new government, as the country's participation in the euro area "is at stake", he added.
As a result, Mr Papadémos has foreseen that the country's public deficit will be reduced to "about 9%" of GDP by the end of the year, after having been 10.6% in 2010 and 15.7% in 2009.
The right rejects new austerity measures
Antonis Samaras, the leader of the right, gave his support on Monday to the measures already approved to try to get out of the debt crisis but warned that his party would not commit to an additional austerity.
"We will not vote in favour of new measures," he said at a meeting with members of his party, New Democracy.
He agreed with the objectives of reducing deficit and debt, and combating waste but hostile to any policy that would prevent economic recovery.
In Olli Rehn, the European Commissioner for Economic and Monetary Affairs, who warned that the IMF and the EU would not release the necessary 8 billion euro loan without written assurance from all parties that they would support the measures envisaged, Antonio Samaras replied that his speech was sufficient and that he would not sign anything under external pressure.
Euthanasia and assisted suicide must be legalized, says a committee of experts
Canadians live in denial of death, according to the Royal Society of Canada report
In palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions, and doctors to work together to ensure better palliative care, beyond cancer.
Canadian society lives in denial of death.
Only 9% of Canadians agree to talk to their doctor about the conditions under which they want to die and make arrangements to do so.
This is one of the conclusions of an impressive report by the Royal Society of Canada, in which six experts from a variety of fields, including ethics, law and medicine, participated.
This committee recommends that the government amend the Criminal Code to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, where appropriate, to a patient who is deemed competent to make such a decision.
From the outset, experts cite a recent survey of the Economy Intelligence Unit, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
If Canada has ranked 10th, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has generated a culture in which people are afraid to address the subject of death."
Medicalization or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, we report experts mandated by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite most Canadians' desire to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying in the hospital.
This rate is highest in Quebec overall, with 86% of the deaths occurring in the hospital.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report come to conclusions that go against the position of the federal government, which has already said that it does not want to change anything in the Criminal Code concerning euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who have also reviewed all countries where these approaches are legalized or decriminalized, there is no evidence that decriminalization leads to abuse in the application, i.e. the practice of euthanasia or suicide assisted by non-competent or non-consenting persons.
On the contrary, yesterday in teleconference Jocelyn Downie, co-signator of the report, would find more cases of these overflows precisely in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalized.
"Euthanasia is practised in Canada, where it is clearly illegal."
"Assisted suicide is practised in Canada, where it is clearly illegal," explains Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians in favor of euthanasia
It should be recalled that 85% of Canadians have already spoken in favour of euthanasia because they believe that it would allow end-of-life people to alleviate their suffering, according to an Angus Reid poll conducted in 2010.
And 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not have the effect of sending the message that the lives of older or disabled people have less value.
As for those who have committed assisted suicide, the respondents estimate that 41% should not be prosecuted.
With regard to the maintenance or cessation of care to a patient, the situation is less clear, the authors say.
