As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron recall in a recent book summarizing the latest knowledge about immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
Restricting anemia immigration growth and hindering employment.
Concerns about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that they may replace national workers, especially the low-skilled, with downward pressure on their wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes for national employees, mainly in occupations in sectors with a lack of employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national employees, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not follow the supply of jobs.
A positive effect on wages
In the same way that a surgeon will have difficulty working in a country with a shortage of anaesthesiologists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants make immigrants' arrivals have a positive effect on the salaries and employment of nationals.
