North Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The North Stream gas pipeline, directly connecting Western Europe to Russia by going to the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has entered into service.
It must provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with brilliance.
More than 500 guests of whom four heads of state and government participated on the Baltic coast last Tuesday, between orchestra and fine buffet, at the inauguration of the North Stream, this new pipeline that directly connects Russia to Germany under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte together turned the steering wheel of the valve commanding the entry of Russian gas into the western European network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic metres of Russian gas will arrive every year in Western Europe with a first 1,224 km tube linking the St Petersburg region to the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube is to be completed by the end of 2012, allowing a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, equivalent to all French consumption.
And we are already talking about the possibility of building a third one on the same path.
For Gazprom, the completion in time and time of this huge construction project looks like victory.
The project had been strongly contested by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The North Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding any land passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries lose some of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close their access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the North Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, whether the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of its supplies.
But it is at the cost of a weakening of Europe's energy, as the project has created a break between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has succeeded in achieving its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which are heavily gas-consuming, and whose deposits are declining.
" This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically, " confirmed François Fillon by inaugurating this pipeline, demonstrating how political and economic major gas contracts are.
All this explains the wide smiles displayed by Gazprom leaders, present in number in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The underwater tube is made of concrete-coated steel to protect it from anchors of ships.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at an average of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to the Second World War.
" A hundred had to be removed or destroyed, as a precaution," says Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
There was also a need to increase measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy like 242 Eiffel towers, which nothing interrupts throughout its length: no valve, no maintenance station.
A monitoring platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project officials gave up while the Swedes were unwilling to see a Russian state-owned company permanently set up off their coasts.
" In case of damage, we stop the gas passage in less than a minute, " says Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, the gas contained in the pipeline is therefore leaked into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who have planned the welds for a leak every 100,000 years.
Monitoring the condition of the pipeline is carried out by an underwater robot, dragged by a ship, for external observation, as well as by a device circulating inside the pipeline.
In the form of a cigar, it is inserted inside the tube, width of one meter in diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of 3 meters second, it delivers precise information on possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without having to undergo any repair.
Gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
It is 200 bars at the start, and 100 at the finish.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, who keeps 51% of the shares.
The German E.ON and BASF (15.5%), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each) joined.
These five companies have created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then rented to this company, for twenty years renewable, the full capacity of gas transport.
" Gazprom will pay for total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported, " says Jens Müller.
Funding for the construction of the pipeline was provided to 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the works is expected to reach € 7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to return to their costs, since only Gazprom assumes the risk.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pines.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the exit door of the gas.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the gas coming before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has received one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour passing.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, a brand name book.
Created about fifteen years ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to restore the taste of writing.
He has a scent of adventures, of hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, elastic, broken white leaves, as aged by time.
