A success that has made us envious: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the SG Capital Europe investment fund, today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskine's history.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week for the employment of disabled people opens today.
Despite a voluntary public policy established in 2005, the unemployment rate for persons with disabilities is twice as high as the average: 19%, compared with 9% for the general population.
Dishearsing?
" No, " says Éric Blanchet, CEO of the Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled. "
" The progress made over the past fifteen years is considerable. "
" At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher. "
" Nevertheless, much remains to be done. "
It has to be said that for the unemployed with disabilities, there are still many obstacles before access to employment.
They are rather old: 37% are over 50 years of age (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have the baccalaureate and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared to an average of 38%.
In short, so many criteria which make it particularly difficult to return to employment, and which " constitute the node of the problem", according to Christian Grabin, Director General of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
That's for objective brakes.
It remains the unsaid, the attitudes that change, of course, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité association indicated that the managers interviewed have "a low level of knowledge of disability", with "overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, psychic or intellectual deficits".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, set out in a law of... 1987.
The last known figures, which date back to 2008, indicate a ratio of 2.6%.
" We are now around 3%, " says Pierre Blanc, Director General of the Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The evidence: the number of "taxed" establishments, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
" The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on businesses, " explains Pierre Blanc. "
" But this improvement also translates into real awareness, especially in large groups. "
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared to 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
